Right, guys?

762
00:58:01,676 --> 00:58:04,178
So put the knife down.
Brooks, look at me.

763
00:58:04,346 --> 00:58:06,680
Put the knife down.

764
00:58:08,600 --> 00:58:10,684
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

765
00:58:11,436 --> 00:58:13,771
Look at his neck. He's bleeding.

766
00:58:14,689 --> 00:58:16,148
It's the only...

767
00:58:16,358 --> 00:58:18,400
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

768
00:58:18,693 --> 00:58:21,028
This is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

769
00:58:21,279 --> 00:58:23,364
Put it... Put it down.

770
00:58:32,124 --> 00:58:33,624
Take it easy.

771
00:58:34,292 --> 00:58:35,876
You'll be all right.

772
00:58:36,044 --> 00:58:38,504
Him? What about me?

773
00:58:38,713 --> 00:58:41,090
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat!

774
00:58:41,299 --> 00:58:43,217
You've had worse from shaving.

775
00:58:43,385 --> 00:58:45,511
What did you do to set him off?

776
00:58:45,720 --> 00:58:47,930
Nothing. I come in here to say farewell.

777
00:58:48,557 --> 00:58:51,225
Ain't you heard?
His parole's come through.

778
00:58:53,395 --> 00:58:56,355
I just don't understand
what happened in there, that's all.

779
00:58:56,523 --> 00:58:59,358
Old man's crazy as a rat
in a tin shithouse.

780
00:58:59,568 --> 00:59:01,443
That's enough out of you.

781
00:59:01,653 --> 00:59:04,405
- Heard he had you shitting your pants.
- Fuck you.

782
00:59:04,656 --> 00:59:05,865
Knock it off.

783
00:59:06,825 --> 00:59:08,242
Brooks ain't no bug.

784
00:59:12,080 --> 00:59:13,873
He's just institutionalized.

785
00:59:15,250 --> 00:59:17,168
"Institutionalized," my ass.

786
00:59:17,377 --> 00:59:21,380
The man's been in here 50 years,
Heywood, 50 years!

787
00:59:21,590 --> 00:59:23,299
This is all he knows.

788
00:59:23,508 --> 00:59:25,801
In here, he's an important man...

789
00:59:26,011 --> 00:59:27,094
an educated man.

790
00:59:27,929 --> 00:59:29,847
Outside, he's nothing.

791
00:59:30,724 --> 00:59:34,226
Just a used-up con
with arthritis in both hands.

792
00:59:34,436 --> 00:59:37,438
Probably couldn't get a library card
if he tried.

793
00:59:37,689 --> 00:59:39,440
You know what I'm trying to say?

794
00:59:39,691 --> 00:59:42,610
I do believe
you're talking out of your ass.

795
00:59:43,862 --> 00:59:46,113
You believe whatever you want.

796
00:59:46,698 --> 00:59:49,116
But I tell you these walls are funny.

797
00:59:50,702 --> 00:59:52,369
First you hate them.

798
00:59:54,206 --> 00:59:56,123
Then you get used to them.

799
00:59:58,043 --> 01:00:00,044
Enough time passes...

800
01:00:00,712 --> 01:00:02,713
you get so you depend on them.

801
01:00:03,715 --> 01:00:05,925
That's "institutionalized."

802
01:00:06,134 --> 01:00:07,426
Shit.

803
01:00:07,636 --> 01:00:10,387
- I could never get like that.
- Oh, yeah?

804
01:00:11,264 --> 01:00:13,766
Wait till you've been here
as long as Brooks.

805
01:00:13,975 --> 01:00:15,559
Goddamn right.

806
01:00:18,146 --> 01:00:20,064
They send you here for life...

807
01:00:20,732 --> 01:00:23,067
that's exactly what they take.

808
01:00:24,819 --> 01:00:26,820
Part that counts, anyway.

809
01:00:34,412 --> 01:00:37,331
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

810
01:00:38,500 --> 01:00:40,167
You go on now.

811
01:00:41,419 --> 01:00:45,756
You're free.

812
01:01:04,776 --> 01:01:06,443
Good luck, Brooksie.

813
01:01:08,738 --> 01:01:10,823
Take care of yourself, Brooks.

814
01:01:44,399 --> 01:01:45,899
Dear fellas:

815
01:01:46,192 --> 01:01:50,404
I can't believe how fast things move
on the outside.

816
01:01:51,698 --> 01:01:54,366
Watch it, old-timer! Want to get killed?

817
01:01:55,577 --> 01:01:59,079
I saw an automobile once
when I was a kid...

818
01:01:59,748 --> 01:02:02,166
but now they're everywhere.

819
01:02:05,837 --> 01:02:10,132
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

820
01:02:25,940 --> 01:02:29,735
The parole board
got me into this halfway house...

821
01:02:30,028 --> 01:02:33,072
called "The Brewer"...
and a job...

822
01:02:33,281 --> 01:02:36,241
bagging groceries at the Food-Way.

823
01:02:37,786 --> 01:02:40,204
It's hard work and I try to keep up...

824
01:02:40,413 --> 01:02:42,790
but my hands hurt most of the time.

825
01:02:43,083 --> 01:02:45,042
Make sure your man double-bags.

826
01:02:45,251 --> 01:02:47,294
Last time, the bottom near came out.

827
01:02:47,962 --> 01:02:50,881
Make sure you double-bag
like the lady says. Understand?

828
01:02:51,091 --> 01:02:52,466
Yes, sir. Surely will.

829
01:02:52,634 --> 01:02:56,178
I don't think the store manager
likes me very much.

830
01:02:59,182 --> 01:03:03,477
Sometimes after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

831
01:03:03,937 --> 01:03:05,437
I keep thinking...

832
01:03:05,647 --> 01:03:08,982
Jake might just show up
and say hello.

833
01:03:09,609 --> 01:03:11,610
But he never does.

834
01:03:12,821 --> 01:03:17,658
I hope, wherever he is, he's doing okay
and making new friends.

835
01:03:21,287 --> 01:03:23,997
I have trouble sleeping at night.

836
01:03:24,332 --> 01:03:27,584
I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.

837
01:03:27,836 --> 01:03:30,087
I wake up scared.

838
01:03:30,296 --> 01:03:34,508
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

839
01:03:36,010 --> 01:03:40,931
Maybe I should get me a gun and rob
the Food-Way so they'd send me home.

840
01:03:41,224 --> 01:03:45,561
I could shoot the manager while
I was at it. Sort of like a bonus.

841
01:03:47,230 --> 01:03:51,233
I guess I'm too old
for that sort of nonsense anymore.

842
01:03:51,484 --> 01:03:53,193
I don't like it here.

843
01:03:53,403 --> 01:03:57,406
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.
I've decided...

844
01:03:58,241 --> 01:03:59,908
not to stay.

845
01:04:10,837 --> 01:04:13,380
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss...

846
01:04:13,590 --> 01:04:17,092
not for an old crook like me.

847
01:05:19,572 --> 01:05:23,825
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss,
not for an old crook like me."

848
01:05:24,869 --> 01:05:28,705
P.S. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

849
01:05:28,915 --> 01:05:31,250
"No hard feelings. Brooks."

850
01:05:41,719 --> 01:05:43,679
He should have died in here.

851
01:05:49,227 --> 01:05:50,644
What the fuck have you done?

852
01:05:50,812 --> 01:05:53,480
It's a goddamn mess,
I'll tell you that.

853
01:05:59,028 --> 01:06:02,781
- What's all this?
- You tell me. They're addressed to you.

854
01:06:04,033 --> 01:06:05,367
Take it.

855
01:06:13,918 --> 01:06:15,419
"Dear Mr. Dufresne:"

856
01:06:16,546 --> 01:06:18,505
In response to your repeated inquiries...

857
01:06:18,715 --> 01:06:23,010
"...the state has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project."

858
01:06:23,761 --> 01:06:25,596
This is $200.

859
01:06:25,805 --> 01:06:29,808
"In addition, the library district
has generously responded..."

860
01:06:30,018 --> 01:06:32,561
with a donation of used books
and sundries.

861
01:06:32,770 --> 01:06:36,898
We trust this will fill your needs.
We now consider the matter closed.

862
01:06:37,108 --> 01:06:38,984
"Please stop sending us letters."

863
01:06:39,152 --> 01:06:41,820
Clear all this out
before the warden gets back.

864
01:06:42,030 --> 01:06:43,196
Yes, sir.

865
01:06:47,493 --> 01:06:48,660
Good for you, Andy.

866
01:06:53,958 --> 01:06:55,876
It only took six years.

867
01:06:57,462 --> 01:07:00,213
From now on, I'll write two
letters a week instead of one.

868
01:07:00,381 --> 01:07:03,717
I believe you're crazy enough.
Get this stuff out...

869
01:07:04,010 --> 01:07:06,428
like he said.
I've got to pinch a loaf.

870
01:07:06,638 --> 01:07:08,096
When I come back...

871
01:07:08,306 --> 01:07:10,057
this is all gone, all right?

872
01:07:58,815 --> 01:08:00,232
Do you hear that?

873
01:09:08,968 --> 01:09:10,135
Dufresne!

874
01:09:12,680 --> 01:09:14,181
Andy, let me out!

875
01:09:21,063 --> 01:09:26,026
I have no idea to this day what those
two Italian ladies were singing about.

876
01:09:26,319 --> 01:09:28,528
Truth is, I don't want to know.

877
01:09:28,738 --> 01:09:31,239
Some things are best left unsaid.

878
01:09:34,827 --> 01:09:37,537
I like to think it was something
so beautiful...

879
01:09:37,747 --> 01:09:39,873
it can't be expressed in words...

880
01:09:40,082 --> 01:09:43,001
and makes your heart ache
because of it.

881
01:09:44,670 --> 01:09:47,172
I tell you, those voices soared...

882
01:09:47,423 --> 01:09:51,718
higher and farther than anybody
in a gray place dares to dream.

883
01:09:51,928 --> 01:09:55,305
It was like a beautiful bird
flapped into our drab cage...

884
01:09:55,515 --> 01:09:58,266
and made those walls dissolve away.

885
01:09:58,726 --> 01:10:00,894
And for the briefest of moments...

886
01:10:01,103 --> 01:10:04,105
every last man at Shawshank felt free.

887
01:10:06,692 --> 01:10:09,361
It pissed the warden off
something awful.

888
01:10:10,655 --> 01:10:11,655
Open the door.

889
01:10:14,575 --> 01:10:16,326
Open it up!

890
01:10:17,620 --> 01:10:20,372
Dufresne, open this door!

891
01:10:21,707 --> 01:10:22,916
Turn that off!

892
01:10:29,966 --> 01:10:32,425
I am warning you. Turn that off!

893
01:10:50,152 --> 01:10:51,695
You're mine now.

894
01:10:59,120 --> 01:11:02,372
Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

895
01:11:02,582 --> 01:11:04,165
On your feet.

896
01:11:05,334 --> 01:11:07,752
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

897
01:11:09,505 --> 01:11:13,174
You couldn't play something good, huh?
Like Hank Williams?

898
01:11:13,509 --> 01:11:16,303
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

899
01:11:16,512 --> 01:11:19,639
- Was it worth two weeks?
- Easiest time I ever did.

900
01:11:19,849 --> 01:11:24,060
- No such thing as easy time in the hole.
- A week in the hole is like a year.

901
01:11:24,270 --> 01:11:27,564
- Damn straight.
- I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

902
01:11:27,773 --> 01:11:30,734
So they let you tote
that record player down there, huh?

903
01:11:33,154 --> 01:11:34,529
It was in here.

904
01:11:35,364 --> 01:11:36,615
In here.

905
01:11:37,742 --> 01:11:39,826
That's the beauty of music. They...

906
01:11:40,036 --> 01:11:42,370
can't get that from you.

907
01:11:45,917 --> 01:11:48,293
Haven't you ever felt
that way about music?

908
01:11:50,087 --> 01:11:53,214
Well, I played a mean harmonica
as a younger man.

909
01:11:54,258 --> 01:11:55,967
Lost interest in it, though.

910
01:11:56,177 --> 01:11:57,761
Didn't make much sense in here.

911
01:11:58,095 --> 01:12:00,096
Here's where it makes the most sense.

912
01:12:00,640 --> 01:12:02,682
You need it so you don't forget.

913
01:12:03,267 --> 01:12:04,559
Forget?

914
01:12:04,852 --> 01:12:09,564
Forget that there are...
places...

915
01:12:10,066 --> 01:12:13,902
in the world
that aren't made out of stone.

916
01:12:14,904 --> 01:12:16,404
There's something...

917
01:12:16,739 --> 01:12:18,156
inside...

918
01:12:18,407 --> 01:12:20,367
that they can't get to...

919
01:12:20,576 --> 01:12:21,993
that they can't touch.

920
01:12:22,495 --> 01:12:23,912
That's yours.

921
01:12:25,456 --> 01:12:27,040
What are you talking about?

922
01:12:28,084 --> 01:12:31,711
Hope.

923
01:12:33,673 --> 01:12:35,674
Let me tell you something, my friend.

924
01:12:36,467 --> 01:12:38,760
Hope is a dangerous thing.

925
01:12:39,929 --> 01:12:42,263
Hope can drive a man insane.

926
01:12:43,015 --> 01:12:45,141
It's got no use on the inside.

927
01:12:45,351 --> 01:12:47,560
You'd better get used to that idea.

928
01:12:50,064 --> 01:12:51,564
Like Brooks did?

929
01:13:16,924 --> 01:13:17,924
Sit down.

930
01:13:23,264 --> 01:13:26,558
Says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

931
01:13:27,727 --> 01:13:29,769
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

932
01:13:29,979 --> 01:13:31,229
Oh, yes, sir.

933
01:13:32,481 --> 01:13:33,815
Without a doubt.

934
01:13:34,984 --> 01:13:37,402
I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

935
01:13:39,405 --> 01:13:41,322
No danger to society here.

936
01:13:41,866 --> 01:13:43,408
God's honest truth.

937
01:13:45,953 --> 01:13:48,079
Absolutely rehabilitated.

938
01:13:58,049 --> 01:13:59,382
Thirty years.

939
01:14:01,343 --> 01:14:03,261
Jesus, when you say it like that...

940
01:14:04,138 --> 01:14:05,930
You wonder where it went.

941
01:14:08,350 --> 01:14:10,518
I wonder where 10 years went.

942
01:14:15,483 --> 01:14:16,524
Here.

943
01:14:16,984 --> 01:14:19,694
A little parole rejection present.

944
01:14:20,988 --> 01:14:22,655
Go ahead and open it.

945
01:14:23,783 --> 01:14:25,825
Went through one of your competitors.

946
01:14:25,993 --> 01:14:29,162
I hope you don't mind.
I wanted it to be a surprise.

947
01:14:39,173 --> 01:14:40,673
It's very pretty.

948
01:14:42,384 --> 01:14:43,593
Thank you.

949
01:14:46,180 --> 01:14:47,639
You going to play it?

950
01:14:52,186 --> 01:14:53,478
No.

951
01:14:57,066 --> 01:14:58,483
Not right now.

952
01:15:16,168 --> 01:15:17,252
Roll in!

953
01:15:53,455 --> 01:15:54,706
Lights out!

954
01:16:29,283 --> 01:16:31,451
Andy was as good as his word.

955
01:16:31,785 --> 01:16:34,579
He wrote two letters a week
instead of one.

956
01:16:36,624 --> 01:16:40,752
In 1959, the state senate
finally clued in to the fact...

957
01:16:40,961 --> 01:16:44,130
they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.

958
01:16:44,298 --> 01:16:48,635
Appropriations Committee
voted an annual payment of $500...

959
01:16:48,802 --> 01:16:50,720
just to shut him up.

960
01:16:50,930 --> 01:16:53,932
And you'd be amazed how far
Andy could stretch it.

961
01:16:54,141 --> 01:16:57,060
He made deals with book clubs,
charity groups.

962
01:16:57,269 --> 01:17:00,021
He bought remaindered books
by the pound...

963
01:17:00,522 --> 01:17:02,065
Treasure Island.

964
01:17:02,608 --> 01:17:05,151
Robert Louis... Stevenson.

965
01:17:05,361 --> 01:17:06,778
Fiction, adventure.

966
01:17:09,323 --> 01:17:10,365
What's next?

967
01:17:10,532 --> 01:17:13,618
I got here Auto Repair...

968
01:17:14,328 --> 01:17:15,495
and Soap Carving.

969
01:17:15,704 --> 01:17:18,957
Trade skills and hobbies.
Under "Educational," behind you.

970
01:17:19,166 --> 01:17:21,000
Count of Monte Crisco.

971
01:17:21,502 --> 01:17:23,795
That's "Cristo," you dumb shit.

972
01:17:24,880 --> 01:17:25,880
By Alexandree...

973
01:17:26,340 --> 01:17:27,632
Dum-ass.

974
01:17:27,967 --> 01:17:29,008
Dumb-ass.

975
01:17:31,303 --> 01:17:32,345
Dumb-ass?

976
01:17:35,266 --> 01:17:37,225
Dumas. Know what that's about?

977
01:17:39,520 --> 01:17:41,521
You'd like it. It's about a prison break.

978
01:17:41,689 --> 01:17:45,566
We ought to file that
under "Educational" too, oughtn't we?

979
01:17:46,443 --> 01:17:50,530
The rest of us did our best
to pitch in when and where we could.

980
01:17:51,115 --> 01:17:52,865
By the year Kennedy was shot...

981
01:17:53,117 --> 01:17:57,620
Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of turpentine...

982
01:17:57,913 --> 01:18:01,040
into the best prison library
in New England...

983
01:18:01,709 --> 01:18:04,669
complete with a fine selection
of Hank Williams.

984
01:18:12,052 --> 01:18:13,970
That was also when Warden Norton...

985
01:18:14,179 --> 01:18:17,098
instituted his famous
"Inside Out" program.

986
01:18:17,558 --> 01:18:19,642
You may remember reading about it.

987
01:18:19,893 --> 01:18:22,979
It made the papers
and got his picture in Look magazine.

988
01:18:23,188 --> 01:18:24,522
It's no free ride...

989
01:18:24,690 --> 01:18:27,900
but rather a genuine
progressive advance...

990
01:18:28,110 --> 01:18:30,611
in corrections and rehabilitation.

991
01:18:30,946 --> 01:18:33,489
Our inmates, properly supervised...

992
01:18:33,699 --> 01:18:36,326
will be put to work
outside these walls...

993
01:18:36,535 --> 01:18:39,620
performing all manner
of public service.

994
01:18:39,788 --> 01:18:42,582
These men can learn the value
of an honest day's labor...

995
01:18:42,791 --> 01:18:46,586
while providing a valuable service
to the community...

996
01:18:46,795 --> 01:18:51,507
and at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. and Mrs. John Q. Taxpayer.

997
01:18:51,925 --> 01:18:54,260
Of course he didn't tell the press...

998
01:18:54,470 --> 01:18:57,930
that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

999
01:18:58,140 --> 01:19:01,184
There are 100 different ways
to skim off the top.

1000
01:19:01,393 --> 01:19:03,895
Men, materials, you name it.

1001
01:19:04,229 --> 01:19:07,106
And oh, my Lord,
how the money rolled in!

1002
01:19:07,316 --> 01:19:09,859
At this rate,
you'll put me out of business.

1003
01:19:10,069 --> 01:19:14,489
With this pool of slave labor,
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1004
01:19:15,074 --> 01:19:18,034
We're providing
a valuable community service.

1005
01:19:18,243 --> 01:19:21,913
That's fine for the papers,
but I've got a family to feed.

1006
01:19:24,583 --> 01:19:26,125
We go back a long way.

1007
01:19:27,419 --> 01:19:32,340
I need this highway contract. I don't
get it and I go under. That's a fact.

1008
01:19:33,258 --> 01:19:35,051
You have some of this fine pie...

1009
01:19:35,302 --> 01:19:38,638
my missus made for you.
You think about that.

1010
01:19:46,897 --> 01:19:49,607
I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1011
01:19:49,817 --> 01:19:52,902
It seems to me I already got my boys
committed elsewhere.

1012
01:19:54,863 --> 01:19:57,949
You be sure and thank Maisie
for this fine pie.

1013
01:19:59,034 --> 01:20:01,202
And behind every shady deal...

1014
01:20:01,537 --> 01:20:04,163
behind every dollar earned...

1015
01:20:04,456 --> 01:20:07,500
there was Andy, keeping the books.

