01:34:48,214 --> 01:34:51,049
Skeets, come on.
Give me that, you shithead.

1260
01:34:51,884 --> 01:34:53,218
Floyd, come on.

1261
01:34:58,641 --> 01:35:01,059
Will you throw that away, please?

1262
01:35:06,649 --> 01:35:08,400
Well, shit.

1263
01:35:21,080 --> 01:35:23,874
The kid passed. C-plus average.

1264
01:35:24,083 --> 01:35:26,168
Thought you'd like to know.

1265
01:35:42,393 --> 01:35:43,852
Warden wants to talk.

1266
01:35:57,617 --> 01:35:58,658
Out here?

1267
01:35:58,868 --> 01:36:01,119
That's what the man said.

1268
01:36:17,220 --> 01:36:18,470
Warden?

1269
01:36:28,231 --> 01:36:32,317
I'm asking you to keep this conversation
just between us.

1270
01:36:33,820 --> 01:36:36,071
I feel awkward enough as it is.

1271
01:36:54,507 --> 01:36:56,591
We got a situation here.

1272
01:36:57,468 --> 01:36:59,553
I think you can appreciate that.

1273
01:36:59,762 --> 01:37:01,012
Yes, sir.

1274
01:37:01,264 --> 01:37:02,681
I sure can.

1275
01:37:02,932 --> 01:37:06,977
I tell you, son, this thing really
came along and knocked my wind out.

1276
01:37:08,438 --> 01:37:11,022
It's got me up nights. That's the truth.

1277
01:37:13,276 --> 01:37:15,110
The right thing to do...

1278
01:37:16,779 --> 01:37:20,532
sometimes it's hard to know
what that is.

1279
01:37:21,534 --> 01:37:22,951
Do you understand?

1280
01:37:25,246 --> 01:37:26,872
I need your help, son.

1281
01:37:28,291 --> 01:37:30,459
If I'm going to move on this...

1282
01:37:30,793 --> 01:37:33,962
there can't be
the least little shred of doubt.

1283
01:37:34,714 --> 01:37:35,755
I have to know...

1284
01:37:35,923 --> 01:37:38,592
if what you told Dufresne
was the truth.

1285
01:37:38,801 --> 01:37:39,926
Yes, sir.

1286
01:37:40,136 --> 01:37:41,386
Absolutely.

1287
01:37:41,888 --> 01:37:44,890
Would you be willing to swear
before a judge and jury...

1288
01:37:45,057 --> 01:37:47,058
with your hand on the Good Book...

1289
01:37:47,268 --> 01:37:49,936
and take an oath
before Almighty God himself?

1290
01:37:50,146 --> 01:37:51,938
Just give me that chance.

1291
01:37:56,235 --> 01:37:57,569
That's what I thought.

1292
01:38:44,617 --> 01:38:46,535
I'm sure by now you've heard.

1293
01:38:48,287 --> 01:38:49,329
Terrible thing.

1294
01:38:50,957 --> 01:38:52,415
A man that young...

1295
01:38:52,750 --> 01:38:55,335
less than a year to go,
trying to escape.

1296
01:38:55,878 --> 01:38:58,380
Broke Captain Hadley's heart
to shoot him.

1297
01:38:59,131 --> 01:39:00,632
Truly, it did.

1298
01:39:03,636 --> 01:39:06,054
We just have to put it behind us.

1299
01:39:07,723 --> 01:39:08,974
Move on.

1300
01:39:10,560 --> 01:39:12,060
I'm done.

1301
01:39:13,354 --> 01:39:14,980
Everything stops.

1302
01:39:16,983 --> 01:39:19,317
Get someone else to run your scams.

1303
01:39:20,570 --> 01:39:22,404
Nothing stops.

1304
01:39:23,739 --> 01:39:25,115
Nothing.

1305
01:39:28,327 --> 01:39:31,413
Or you will do the hardest time there is.

1306
01:39:31,831 --> 01:39:34,165
No more protection from the guards.

1307
01:39:34,333 --> 01:39:39,254
I'll pull you out of that 1 -bunk Hilton
and cast you down with the sodomites.

1308
01:39:40,673 --> 01:39:43,091
You'll think you've been
fucked by a train.

1309
01:39:44,510 --> 01:39:46,011
And the library?

1310
01:39:46,679 --> 01:39:47,679
Gone.

1311
01:39:48,264 --> 01:39:50,849
Sealed off, brick by brick.

1312
01:39:51,309 --> 01:39:53,977
We'll have us a little
book barbecue in the yard.

1313
01:39:54,186 --> 01:39:56,313
They'll see the flames for miles.

1314
01:39:56,522 --> 01:39:59,357
We'll dance around it like wild lnjuns.

1315
01:40:00,610 --> 01:40:03,612
You understand me? Catching my drift?

1316
01:40:07,366 --> 01:40:09,200
Or am I being obtuse?

1317
01:40:21,005 --> 01:40:23,632
Give him another month
to think about it.

1318
01:41:10,388 --> 01:41:13,431
My wife used to say
I'm a hard man to know.

1319
01:41:14,266 --> 01:41:16,101
Like a closed book.

1320
01:41:16,894 --> 01:41:18,937
Complained about it all the time.

1321
01:41:19,855 --> 01:41:21,439
She was beautiful.

1322
01:41:23,818 --> 01:41:25,652
God, I loved her.

1323
01:41:29,073 --> 01:41:31,282
I didn't know how to show it, that's all.

1324
01:41:34,036 --> 01:41:35,704
I killed her, Red.

1325
01:41:37,581 --> 01:41:39,374
I didn't pull the trigger...

1326
01:41:40,793 --> 01:41:42,544
but I drove her away.

1327
01:41:44,046 --> 01:41:46,756
That's why she died, because of me...

1328
01:41:46,924 --> 01:41:48,299
the way I am.

1329
01:41:57,309 --> 01:41:59,144
That don't make you a murderer.

1330
01:42:02,523 --> 01:42:04,315
Bad husband, maybe.

1331
01:42:07,945 --> 01:42:11,197
Feel bad about it if you want,
but you didn't pull the trigger.

1332
01:42:11,407 --> 01:42:12,741
No, I didn't.

1333
01:42:13,159 --> 01:42:15,076
Somebody else did.

1334
01:42:16,328 --> 01:42:18,413
And I wound up in here.

1335
01:42:20,875 --> 01:42:22,500
Bad luck, I guess.

1336
01:42:27,673 --> 01:42:29,132
It floats around.

1337
01:42:30,176 --> 01:42:32,385
It's got to land on somebody.

1338
01:42:33,304 --> 01:42:35,180
It was my turn, that's all.

1339
01:42:35,890 --> 01:42:38,683
I was in the path of the tornado.

1340
01:42:44,607 --> 01:42:48,568
I just didn't expect the storm
would last as long as it has.

1341
01:42:52,907 --> 01:42:54,616
Think you'll ever get out of here?

1342
01:42:55,868 --> 01:42:57,285
Me?

1343
01:42:59,872 --> 01:43:01,206
Yeah.

1344
01:43:02,208 --> 01:43:04,501
One day, when I got
a long, white beard...

1345
01:43:04,710 --> 01:43:08,797
and two or three marbles rolling
around upstairs, they'll let me out.

1346
01:43:09,882 --> 01:43:11,549
I tell you where I'd go.

1347
01:43:13,010 --> 01:43:14,719
Zihuatanejo.

1348
01:43:15,554 --> 01:43:16,721
Say what?

1349
01:43:17,056 --> 01:43:18,890
Zihuatanejo.

1350
01:43:19,809 --> 01:43:21,476
It's in Mexico.

1351
01:43:22,853 --> 01:43:24,979
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1352
01:43:26,106 --> 01:43:28,900
You know what the Mexicans say
about the Pacific?

1353
01:43:30,736 --> 01:43:32,737
They say it has no memory.

1354
01:43:34,698 --> 01:43:37,367
That's where I want to live
the rest of my life.

1355
01:43:38,994 --> 01:43:41,496
A warm place with no memory.

1356
01:43:44,750 --> 01:43:46,668
Open up a little hotel...

1357
01:43:48,379 --> 01:43:49,879
right on the beach.

1358
01:43:50,464 --> 01:43:52,674
Buy some worthless old boat...

1359
01:43:53,217 --> 01:43:54,843
and fix it up new.

1360
01:43:57,596 --> 01:43:58,805
Take my guests out...

1361
01:43:59,640 --> 01:44:01,015
charter fishing.

1362
01:44:04,854 --> 01:44:06,604
Zihuatanejo.

1363
01:44:10,109 --> 01:44:13,987
In a place like that, I could use
a man that knows how to get things.

1364
01:44:20,536 --> 01:44:23,371
I don't think I could make it
on the outside.

1365
01:44:30,045 --> 01:44:32,130
I been in here most of my life.

1366
01:44:33,549 --> 01:44:35,300
I'm an institutional man now.

1367
01:44:36,218 --> 01:44:37,969
Just like Brooks was.

1368
01:44:39,430 --> 01:44:41,139
You underestimate yourself.

1369
01:44:41,682 --> 01:44:43,308
I don't think so.

1370
01:44:47,146 --> 01:44:51,065
In here I'm the guy who can get things
for you, sure, but...

1371
01:44:51,817 --> 01:44:54,360
outside all you need
is the Yellow Pages.

1372
01:44:54,570 --> 01:44:56,821
Hell, I wouldn't know
where to begin.

1373
01:44:58,949 --> 01:45:00,575
Pacific Ocean?

1374
01:45:00,993 --> 01:45:02,201
Shit.

1375
01:45:02,578 --> 01:45:04,787
Scare me to death, something that big.

1376
01:45:04,997 --> 01:45:06,289
Not me.

1377
01:45:07,499 --> 01:45:10,251
I didn't shoot my wife,
and I didn't shoot her lover.

1378
01:45:12,004 --> 01:45:15,214
Whatever mistakes I made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1379
01:45:16,258 --> 01:45:17,759
That hotel, that boat...

1380
01:45:19,511 --> 01:45:21,763
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1381
01:45:26,685 --> 01:45:29,103
You shouldn't be doing this to yourself.

1382
01:45:29,313 --> 01:45:31,356
This is just shitty pipe dreams.

1383
01:45:31,774 --> 01:45:34,233
Mexico is way down there
and you're in here...

1384
01:45:34,443 --> 01:45:36,027
and that's the way it is.

1385
01:45:36,362 --> 01:45:39,197
Yeah, right. That's the way it is.

1386
01:45:40,699 --> 01:45:43,076
It's down there and I'm in here.

1387
01:45:45,663 --> 01:45:48,373
I guess it comes down
to a simple choice.

1388
01:45:51,293 --> 01:45:52,794
Get busy living...

1389
01:45:54,171 --> 01:45:56,214
or get busy dying.

1390
01:46:08,310 --> 01:46:11,062
If you ever get out of here,
do me a favor.

1391
01:46:11,230 --> 01:46:13,523
Sure, Andy. Anything.

1392
01:46:15,401 --> 01:46:19,237
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1393
01:46:20,739 --> 01:46:23,866
- A lot of hayfields up there.
- One in particular.

1394
01:46:24,076 --> 01:46:27,996
It's got a long rock wall
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1395
01:46:28,205 --> 01:46:31,082
It's like something
out of a Robert Frost poem.

1396
01:46:32,001 --> 01:46:34,502
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1397
01:46:35,921 --> 01:46:38,006
We went there for a picnic...

1398
01:46:38,424 --> 01:46:40,508
and made love under that oak...

1399
01:46:41,176 --> 01:46:43,428
and I asked and she said yes.

1400
01:46:47,433 --> 01:46:49,267
Promise me, Red.

1401
01:46:50,102 --> 01:46:53,438
If you ever get out...
find that spot.

1402
01:46:54,606 --> 01:46:59,444
At the base of that wall, there's a rock
that has no earthly business in Maine.

1403
01:47:00,571 --> 01:47:03,614
Piece of black, volcanic glass.

1404
01:47:06,285 --> 01:47:08,953
Something's buried under it
I want you to have.

1405
01:47:09,705 --> 01:47:10,955
What, Andy?

1406
01:47:11,373 --> 01:47:13,124
What's buried under there?

1407
01:47:14,710 --> 01:47:18,046
You'll have to pry it up...
to see.

1408
01:47:24,053 --> 01:47:25,887
No, I'm telling you. The guy is...

1409
01:47:26,555 --> 01:47:28,306
He's talking funny.

1410
01:47:29,391 --> 01:47:31,100
I'm really worried about him.

1411
01:47:31,477 --> 01:47:32,935
Let's keep an eye on him.

1412
01:47:33,145 --> 01:47:36,397
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's all alone.

1413
01:47:37,816 --> 01:47:38,983
Oh, Lord.

1414
01:47:40,319 --> 01:47:41,903
What?

1415
01:47:42,654 --> 01:47:45,406
Andy come down
to the loading dock today.

1416
01:47:45,616 --> 01:47:47,700
He asked me for a length of rope.

1417
01:47:47,910 --> 01:47:50,620
- Rope?
- Six feet long.

1418
01:47:50,829 --> 01:47:52,205
And you gave it to him.

1419
01:47:53,082 --> 01:47:54,874
Sure. Why wouldn't I?

1420
01:47:55,084 --> 01:47:56,667
Jesus! Heywood.

1421
01:47:57,252 --> 01:47:59,212
How was I supposed to know?

1422
01:47:59,421 --> 01:48:01,005
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1423
01:48:03,008 --> 01:48:04,926
Andy would never do that.

1424
01:48:05,511 --> 01:48:06,969
Never.

1425
01:48:08,680 --> 01:48:10,014
I don't know.

1426
01:48:12,851 --> 01:48:14,852
Every man has his breaking point.

1427
01:48:17,189 --> 01:48:19,482
Lickety-split. Want to get home.

1428
01:48:19,775 --> 01:48:21,526
Just about finished, sir.

1429
01:48:38,669 --> 01:48:40,294
Three deposits tonight.

1430
01:48:48,262 --> 01:48:50,179
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1431
01:48:50,389 --> 01:48:52,014
And shine my shoes.

1432
01:48:52,224 --> 01:48:55,143
- I want them looking like mirrors.
- Yes, sir.

1433
01:49:00,649 --> 01:49:02,108
It's good having you back.

1434
01:49:03,068 --> 01:49:04,902
Place wasn't the same without you.

1435
01:49:51,783 --> 01:49:53,159
Lights out!

1436
01:50:25,692 --> 01:50:28,236
I've had some long nights in the stir.

1437
01:50:28,779 --> 01:50:31,447
Alone in the dark
with nothing but your thoughts...

1438
01:50:31,657 --> 01:50:34,325
time can draw out like a blade.

1439
01:50:39,665 --> 01:50:42,667
That was the longest night of my life.

1440
01:50:58,517 --> 01:50:59,684
Give me a count!

1441
01:51:04,189 --> 01:51:07,024
Tier 3 south, clear!

1442
01:51:10,153 --> 01:51:13,322
Man missing on tier 2, cell 245!

1443
01:51:13,532 --> 01:51:14,573
Dufresne!

1444
01:51:15,117 --> 01:51:17,535
Come out. You're holding up the show!

1445
01:51:20,706 --> 01:51:24,083
Don't make me come down
or I'll thump your skull for you!

1446
01:51:31,675 --> 01:51:35,511
Damn it, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1447
01:51:35,721 --> 01:51:39,015
You'd better be sick or dead in there.
I shit you not!

1448
01:51:39,224 --> 01:51:40,558
You hear me?

1449
01:51:46,648 --> 01:51:48,733
Oh, my Holy God.

1450
01:52:05,751 --> 01:52:08,294
I want every man
on this cellblock questioned.

1451
01:52:08,754 --> 01:52:11,297
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1452
01:52:11,465 --> 01:52:12,882
Him.

1453
01:52:13,884 --> 01:52:15,426
Open 237.

1454
01:52:18,930 --> 01:52:22,600
What do you mean, "He just wasn't here"?
Don't say that to me.

1455
01:52:23,477 --> 01:52:26,062
- Don't say that to me again.
- But, sir, he wasn't.

1456
01:52:26,271 --> 01:52:29,774
I can see that, Haig! Think I'm blind?

1457
01:52:30,442 --> 01:52:32,026
Is that what you're saying?

1458
01:52:32,194 --> 01:52:34,695
- Am I blind, Haig?
- No, sir!

1459
01:52:35,614 --> 01:52:38,115
What about you. You blind?

1460
01:52:38,617 --> 01:52:41,160
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1461
01:52:41,370 --> 01:52:44,663
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. Right there.

1462
01:52:44,873 --> 01:52:46,207
"Dufresne."

1463
01:52:47,876 --> 01:52:50,628
He was in his cell at lights out.

1464
01:52:50,796 --> 01:52:53,714
Stands to reason he'd still be here
in the morning.

1465
01:52:54,049 --> 01:52:55,674
I want him found.

1466
01:52:55,884 --> 01:52:59,345
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast. Now!

1467
01:52:59,596 --> 01:53:00,805
Yes, sir.

1468
01:53:01,807 --> 01:53:05,601
Let's go. Move your butts. Move it!

1469
01:53:07,479 --> 01:53:08,479
Stand.

1470
01:53:09,898 --> 01:53:11,315
Well?

1471
01:53:14,403 --> 01:53:15,444
Well, what?

1472
01:53:15,612 --> 01:53:19,073
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1473
01:53:20,158 --> 01:53:21,659
He must have said something.

1474
01:53:22,369 --> 01:53:25,287
No, sir, warden. Not a word.

1475
01:53:27,082 --> 01:53:29,667
Lord, it's a miracle!

1476
01:53:30,252 --> 01:53:32,837
Man vanished like a fart in the wind.

1477
01:53:33,505 --> 01:53:34,672
Nothing left...

1478
01:53:35,507 --> 01:53:38,217
but some damn rocks
on a windowsill.

1479
01:53:38,427 --> 01:53:41,178
And that cupcake on the wall.
Let's ask her.

1480
01:53:41,346 --> 01:53:43,139
Maybe she knows.

1481
01:53:43,348 --> 01:53:46,100
What say there, fuzzy-britches?
Feel like talking?

1482
01:53:47,519 --> 01:53:48,853
Guess not.

1483
01:53:49,396 --> 01:53:51,605
Why should she be any different?

1484
01:53:52,691 --> 01:53:54,358
This is a conspiracy.

1485
01:53:54,985 --> 01:53:56,694
That's what this is.

1486
01:53:57,404 --> 01:54:01,157
One big, damn conspiracy!

1487
01:54:01,408 --> 01:54:03,409
And everyone's in on it!

1488
01:54:04,035 --> 01:54:05,202
Including her!

1489
01:54:40,238 --> 01:54:44,575
In 1966... Andy
Dufresne escaped...

1490
01:54:44,743 --> 01:54:46,327
from Shawshank Prison.

1491
01:54:48,580 --> 01:54:51,123
All they found
was a muddy set of prison clothes...

1492
01:54:51,750 --> 01:54:55,085
a bar of soap... and
an old rock hammer...

1493
01:54:55,253 --> 01:54:57,755
damn near worn down to the nub.

1494
01:55:02,260 --> 01:55:07,014
I remember thinking it would take a man 600
years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1495
01:55:07,641 --> 01:55:10,267
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1496
01:55:28,578 --> 01:55:30,871
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1497
01:55:31,623 --> 01:55:34,792
I imagine it appealed to
his meticulous nature.

1498
01:55:35,210 --> 01:55:37,044
An ice age here...

1499
01:55:37,462 --> 01:55:39,964
million years
of mountain-building there.

1500
01:55:40,966 --> 01:55:43,801
Geology is the study
of pressure and time.

1501
01:55:44,636 --> 01:55:46,637
That's all it takes, really.

1502
01:55:47,389 --> 01:55:48,681
Pressure...

1503
01:55:49,140 --> 01:55:50,641
and time.

1504
01:55:51,726 --> 01:55:53,811
That and a big goddamn poster.

1505
01:55:57,607 --> 01:55:58,774
Like I said...

1506
01:55:59,276 --> 01:56:03,279
in prison, a man will do anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1507
01:56:06,074 --> 01:56:10,869
Seems Andy's favorite hobby was toting
his wall out into the exercise yard...

1508
01:56:11,413 --> 01:56:13,330
a handful at a time.

1509
01:56:14,666 --> 01:56:16,709
I guess after Tommy was killed...

1510
01:56:16,918 --> 01:56:19,878
Andy decided
he'd been here long enough.

1511
01:56:20,088 --> 01:56:22,673
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1512
01:56:23,383 --> 01:56:25,426
I'm just about finished, sir.

1513
01:56:46,865 --> 01:56:48,824
Three deposits tonight.

1514
01:56:56,124 --> 01:56:58,417
Andy did like he was told.

1515
01:56:58,627 --> 01:57:02,129
Buffed those shoes
to a high mirror-shine.

1516
01:57:05,800 --> 01:57:08,093
The guards simply didn't notice.

1517
01:57:08,386 --> 01:57:09,887
Neither did I.

1518
01:57:10,055 --> 01:57:11,597
I mean, seriously...

1519
01:57:11,806 --> 01:57:14,808
how often do you really look
at a man's shoes?

1520
01:59:18,349 --> 01:59:21,518
Andy crawled to freedom
through 500 yards...

1521
01:59:21,770 --> 01:59:25,105
of shit-smelling foulness
I can't even imagine.

1522
01:59:26,107 --> 01:59:28,442
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1523
01:59:32,864 --> 01:59:35,199
Five hundred yards.

1524
01:59:35,700 --> 01:59:38,786
That's the length
of five football fields.

1525
01:59:39,412 --> 01:59:41,997
Just shy of half a mile.

1526
02:00:37,220 --> 02:00:41,807
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her secret...

1527
02:00:42,100 --> 02:00:44,935
a man nobody ever
laid eyes on before...

1528
02:00:45,186 --> 02:00:47,771
strolled into
the Maine National Bank.

1529
02:00:48,356 --> 02:00:51,525
Until that moment, he didn't exist.

1530
02:00:52,110 --> 02:00:54,444
- Except on paper.
- May I help you?

1531
02:00:54,863 --> 02:00:56,780
He had all the proper ID...

1532
02:00:56,990 --> 02:01:00,701
Driver's license, birth certificate,
Social Security card.

1533
02:01:01,119 --> 02:01:03,662
And the signature
was a spot-on match.

1534
02:01:03,872 --> 02:01:06,957
I must say I'm sorry
to be losing your business.

1535
02:01:07,166 --> 02:01:08,917
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1536
02:01:09,711 --> 02:01:11,295
Thank you.

1537
02:01:11,462 --> 02:01:12,629
I'm sure I will.

1538
02:01:13,548 --> 02:01:16,884
Here's your cashier's check, sir.
Will there be anything else?

1539
02:01:17,093 --> 02:01:18,093
Please.

1540
02:01:18,636 --> 02:01:21,138
Would you add this
to your outgoing mail?

1541
02:01:21,639 --> 02:01:23,181
I'd be happy to.

1542
02:01:24,642 --> 02:01:25,976
Good day, sir.

1543
02:01:26,936 --> 02:01:31,356
Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.

1544
02:01:31,816 --> 02:01:33,442
All told, he blew town...

1545
02:01:33,651 --> 02:01:38,488
with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1546
02:01:39,157 --> 02:01:41,950
Severance pay for 19 years.

1547
02:01:49,167 --> 02:01:51,376
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1548
02:02:44,222 --> 02:02:47,182
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1549
02:02:47,433 --> 02:02:51,895
If you give up this right, anything you
say can be held against you in court.

1550
02:02:52,313 --> 02:02:56,775
I wasn't there to see it, but I hear
Byron Hadley sobbed like a girl...

1551
02:02:56,985 --> 02:02:58,485
when they took him away.

1552
02:03:04,367 --> 02:03:07,744
Norton had no intention
of going that quietly.

1553
02:03:23,720 --> 02:03:25,095
Samuel Norton.

1554
02:03:25,263 --> 02:03:27,681
We have a warrant for your arrest.
Open up.

1555
02:03:32,437 --> 02:03:33,895
Open the door.

1556
02:03:34,063 --> 02:03:35,313
I'm not sure which key.

1557
02:03:45,450 --> 02:03:47,409
Make it easy on yourself, Norton!

1558
02:03:58,921 --> 02:04:02,382
I like to think the last thing
that went through his head...

1559
02:04:02,592 --> 02:04:04,176
other than that bullet...

1560
02:04:04,385 --> 02:04:08,805
was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1561
02:04:11,309 --> 02:04:14,811
Not long after the warden
deprived us of his company...

1562
02:04:15,063 --> 02:04:17,147
I got a postcard in the mail.

1563
02:04:18,608 --> 02:04:21,443
It was blank, but the postmark said...

1564
02:04:21,652 --> 02:04:23,779
Fort Hancock, Texas.

1565
02:04:24,322 --> 02:04:25,655
Fort Hancock...

1566
02:04:25,948 --> 02:04:27,657
right on the border.

1567
02:04:28,076 --> 02:04:30,077
That's where Andy crossed.

1568
02:04:30,661 --> 02:04:34,790
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down...

1569
02:04:35,124 --> 02:04:37,334
it always makes me laugh.

1570
02:04:39,170 --> 02:04:40,754
Andy Dufresne...

1571
02:04:41,130 --> 02:04:43,173
who crawled through
a river of shit...

1572
02:04:43,341 --> 02:04:45,759
and came out clean
on the other side.

1573
02:04:46,594 --> 02:04:47,969
Andy Dufresne...

1574
02:04:48,763 --> 02:04:50,347
headed for the Pacific.

1575
02:04:53,351 --> 02:04:55,519
Hadley's got him
by the throat, right?

1576
02:04:55,686 --> 02:04:59,523
He says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1577
02:04:59,690 --> 02:05:02,567
Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1578
02:05:03,236 --> 02:05:04,945
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1579
02:05:05,154 --> 02:05:08,115
"My friends could use
a couple of beers."

1580
02:05:08,449 --> 02:05:10,117
And he got it!

1581
02:05:11,369 --> 02:05:13,745
Sometimes it makes me sad, though...

1582
02:05:14,038 --> 02:05:15,455
Andy being gone.

1583
02:05:16,165 --> 02:05:20,293
I have to remind myself that
some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1584
02:05:20,753 --> 02:05:22,838
Their feathers are just too bright.

1585
02:05:24,549 --> 02:05:26,258
And when they fly away...

1586
02:05:26,717 --> 02:05:31,096
the part of you that knows it was
a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1587
02:05:32,181 --> 02:05:33,431
But still...

1588
02:05:33,891 --> 02:05:38,228
the place you live in is that much
more drab and empty that they're gone.

1589
02:05:42,441 --> 02:05:44,818
I guess I just miss my friend.

1590
02:06:09,260 --> 02:06:10,427
Please sit down.

1591
02:06:16,267 --> 02:06:17,851
Ellis Boyd Redding...

1592
02:06:18,394 --> 02:06:21,646
your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1593
02:06:22,440 --> 02:06:24,608
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1594
02:06:26,444 --> 02:06:28,028
Rehabilitated?

1595
02:06:30,072 --> 02:06:31,948
Well, now, let me see.

1596
02:06:32,950 --> 02:06:35,285
I don't have any idea what that means.

1597
02:06:37,413 --> 02:06:39,664
It means you're ready
to rejoin society...

1598
02:06:40,249 --> 02:06:42,584
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1599
02:06:44,754 --> 02:06:46,755
To me it's just a made-up word.

1600
02:06:48,090 --> 02:06:50,425
A politician's word so that...

1601
02:06:50,843 --> 02:06:54,387
young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie...

1602
02:06:54,847 --> 02:06:56,473
and have a job.

1603
02:06:58,434 --> 02:07:00,518
What do you really want to know?

1604
02:07:01,312 --> 02:07:03,271
Am I sorry for what I did?

1605
02:07:03,689 --> 02:07:04,981
Well, are you?

1606
02:07:06,776 --> 02:07:09,611
There's not a day goes by
I don't feel regret.

1607
02:07:10,988 --> 02:07:14,449
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1608
02:07:17,912 --> 02:07:20,497
I look back on the way I was then...

1609
02:07:22,625 --> 02:07:23,959
a young...

1610
02:07:24,877 --> 02:07:28,380
stupid kid who committed
that terrible crime.

1611
02:07:31,384 --> 02:07:33,093
I want to talk to him.

1612
02:07:35,012 --> 02:07:37,514
I want to try
and talk some sense to him.

1613
02:07:38,224 --> 02:07:40,183
Tell him the way things are.

1614
02:07:42,270 --> 02:07:43,687
But I can't.

1615
02:07:45,898 --> 02:07:47,899
That kid's long gone...

1616
02:07:49,110 --> 02:07:51,861
and this old man is all that's left.

1617
02:07:53,281 --> 02:07:54,739
I got to live with that.

1618
02:07:56,117 --> 02:07:57,826
Rehabilitated?

1619
02:07:58,202 --> 02:08:00,036
It's just a bullshit word.

1620
02:08:00,955 --> 02:08:05,709
So you go on and stamp your forms,
sonny, and stop wasting my time.

1621
02:08:06,961 --> 02:08:09,212
Because to tell you the truth...

1622
02:08:09,547 --> 02:08:11,548
I don't give a shit.

1623
02:09:38,094 --> 02:09:39,469
Here you go, miss.

1624
02:09:42,431 --> 02:09:43,473
Restroom break?

1625
02:09:49,271 --> 02:09:53,817
You don't need to ask me every time you
need to go take a piss. Just go.

1626
02:09:54,819 --> 02:09:56,444
Yes, sir.

1627
02:10:06,831 --> 02:10:09,916
Forty years I've been asking
permission to piss.

1628
02:10:10,751 --> 02:10:13,753
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1629
02:10:17,258 --> 02:10:19,426
There's a harsh truth to face.

1630
02:10:21,095 --> 02:10:24,013
No way I'm going to make it
on the outside.

1631
02:10:31,856 --> 02:10:35,567
All I do anymore is think of ways
to break my parole...

1632
02:10:36,360 --> 02:10:38,862
so maybe they'd send me back.

1633
02:10:44,034 --> 02:10:46,494
Terrible thing, to live in fear.

1634
02:10:47,371 --> 02:10:49,038
Brooks Hatlen knew it.

1635
02:10:49,248 --> 02:10:51,207
Knew it all too well.

1636
02:10:52,793 --> 02:10:56,212
All I want is to be back
where things make sense.

1637
02:10:56,630 --> 02:10:59,382
Where I won't have to be afraid
all the time.

1638
02:11:01,385 --> 02:11:03,720
Only one thing stops me.

1639
02:11:05,181 --> 02:11:07,557
A promise I made to Andy.

1640
02:11:28,078 --> 02:11:29,412
There it is.

1641
02:11:39,840 --> 02:11:41,508
Much obliged, sir.

1642
02:15:20,811 --> 02:15:22,103
Dear Red:

1643
02:15:22,312 --> 02:15:24,814
If you're reading this,
you've gotten out...

1644
02:15:24,982 --> 02:15:29,152
and if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a bit further.

1645
02:15:29,319 --> 02:15:31,821
You remember the name
of the town, don't you?

1646
02:15:34,116 --> 02:15:35,616
Zihuatanejo.

1647
02:15:37,244 --> 02:15:40,830
I could use a good man
to help me get my project on wheels.

1648
02:15:41,331 --> 02:15:44,876
I'll keep an eye out for you,
and the chessboard ready.

1649
02:15:45,669 --> 02:15:47,086
Remember, Red...

1650
02:15:47,421 --> 02:15:49,505
hope is a good thing...

1651
02:15:49,715 --> 02:15:51,716
maybe the best of things.

1652
02:15:51,925 --> 02:15:54,093
And no good thing ever dies.

1653
02:15:54,636 --> 02:15:57,513
I will be hoping
that this letter finds you...

1654
02:15:57,681 --> 02:15:59,432
and finds you well.

1655
02:15:59,933 --> 02:16:02,518
Your friend... Andy.

1656
02:16:36,386 --> 02:16:40,223
"Get busy living...
or get busy dying."

1657
02:16:42,893 --> 02:16:45,061
That's goddamn right.

1658
02:16:50,317 --> 02:16:52,443
For the second time in my life...

1659
02:16:52,694 --> 02:16:55,238
I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1660
02:16:56,323 --> 02:16:58,241
Parole violation.

1661
02:16:58,909 --> 02:17:02,578
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1662
02:17:03,247 --> 02:17:05,289
Not for an old crook like me.

1663
02:17:05,499 --> 02:17:07,542
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1664
02:17:11,213 --> 02:17:15,925
I find I'm so excited I can barely
sit still or hold a thought in my head.

1665
02:17:16,385 --> 02:17:19,720
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1666
02:17:19,930 --> 02:17:22,431
A free man at the start
of a long journey...

1667
02:17:22,599 --> 02:17:25,226
whose conclusion is uncertain.

1668
02:17:28,230 --> 02:17:30,898
I hope I can make it across the border.

1669
02:17:32,401 --> 02:17:35,444
I hope to see my friend
and shake his hand.

1670
02:17:37,281 --> 02:17:41,367
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1671
02:17:43,203 --> 02:17:44,412
I hope.

1672
02:18:22,115 --> 02:18:29,615
 Thanks for using the subs
     regards, shock

